<TEXT>
president bush spending the holidays at camp 
david md faces a full platter of unfinished business when he 
returns to washington next week and what a difference a year has 
made 
the final days of 1989 found bush enjoying the holiday season on 
a friends ranch in beeville texas basking in the success of the 
us invasion of panama 
the most pressing controversy at the time it seemed was 
whether us armed forces were right to blast the vatican embassy 
in panama city with rock music in an effort to drive manuel noriega 
out of hiding 
the toppled panamanian dictator did flee the embassy into us 
hands in early january and bush saw his approval ratings in public 
opinion polls soar to 80 percent 
now 12 months later complex foreign and domestic policy crises 
confront the president and none of the major problems seem likely 
to have a quick or decisive resolution 
in the past year the president abandoned his nonewtaxes 
pledge got bloodied in a knockdown budget debate with congress and 
saw his party lose seats in the november midterm elections 
he also ordered the largest deployment of us forces since the 
vietnam war watched the nation slip towards a recession and wound 
up taking actions that angered civil rights activists republican 
conservatives environmentalists and broccoli farmers 
the most demanding piece of unfinished business of course is 
the persian gulf crisis and the jan 15 deadline set by the 
united nations at the administrations behest for saddam hussein 
to pull his iraqi troops out of kuwait 
bush has not signaled whether he will mount a military strike 
soon after that date and even though it now appears unlikely the 
united states will act against saddam on jan 15 bush told 
congressional leaders last week that he surely would not wait as 
long as summer 
there have been no signs that saddam is any nearer to buckling 
to the pressure of international sanctions and the usled 400000 
troops deployed against him in saudi arabia and the persian gulf 
after months of dashing around the country and the world bush 
was keeping an unusually low profile in his 11day stay at the 
presidential retreat in the catoctin mountains of maryland about 
60 miles northwest of washington 
he just needs to recharge his batteries said a white house 
official speaking on the condition of anonymity 
hell need fresh batteries for the coming weeks 
congress returns on jan 3 two days after the president and 
his persian gulf policy will be the no 1 topic after both houses 
take care of the business of organizing themselves 
also facing the president is a decision on a budget for fiscal 
1992 the first one under the 500 billion fiveyear 
deficitcutting agreement struck between the white house and 
congress in the fall 
the economic slump and the cost of operation desert shield will 
send the deficit soaring complicating the job of putting together 
a budget the fiscal blueprint will be submitted to congress the 
first week in february 
furthermore bush apparently is going to abandon yet another 
campaign pledge as he works out the new spending plan his call for 
a cut in capital gains taxes 
although the administration contends that cutting the tax rate 
on capital gains profits from the sale of stock real estate or 
other assets would generate growth and gain revenue for the 
treasury it cant prove it 
and under the budget pact anytime a tax cut or spending 
increase is proposed it has to be offset by a tax increase or a 
spending cut in another area ten days ago bush said he would give 
up the capital gains idea because he could not find the savings 
elsewhere in the budget perhaps as much as 20 billion by some 
estimates to pay for it 
some other decisions facing the president 
he must select a new chairman of the republican national 
committee to replace his first choice former national drug policy 
director william bennett who spurned the offer after being told by 
white house lawyers hed have to give up a lucrative book contract 
and outside speaking engagements 
he soon must fill a vacancy on the federal reserve board 
created more than six months ago with the resignation of vice 
chairman manuel johnson 
he must complete work on a longdelayed national energy 
strategy the plan is snagged in an internal administration feud 
over how much the government should involve itself in conservation 
efforts 
