<TEXT>
here are excerpts from recent editorials in newspapers in the 
united states and abroad 
 
dec 23 
the oregonian portland ore on the soviet union 
soviet foreign minister eduard a shevardnadzes surprising 
resignation is a tremendous shock to the west on two counts it 
potentially takes a westernlooking and trusted negotiator from a 
key position shevardnadzes reason a reactionary trend toward 
dictatorship shows how uncertain the soviet unions future 
including its relationship with the west really is 
shevardnadze has been a key associate of soviet president 
mikhail gorbachev and that team has been a good one from the 
western perspective the international result has been breathtaking 
the effective release of eastern europe from the soviet grip and 
the breakup of the warsaw pact as a military force 
within the soviet union however the situation is chaotic a 
political revolution of rising expectations has unleashed yearnings 
for independence among various soviet republics 
the food supply and other economic indicators have gotten worse 
many are calling for forcible imposition of central control 
its no surprise that such disorder brings cries for order at 
any cost but shevardnadzes warning is as chilling for the west as 
for the soviet congress that he issued it to dictatorship is 
coming i say this with all responsibility nobody knows what kind 
of dictatorship it will be and who will come what kind of 
dictator and what kind of system 
from the western perspective the hope is that reform doesnt 
break down in the soviet union the reactionaries shevardnadze 
warned against are likely to hold the old brooding russian view of 
the world particularly the west as a threat and never to be 
trusted 
the best policy for the west is one of benign noninterference 
to show we are ready to be friends with whatever manifestation the 
soviet union takes if it is equally ready 
we can hope for reform but must be ready to work with whatever 
results 
 
dec 24 
the birmingham ala news on the soviet union 
shevardnadzes resignation on principle certainly is 
something we havent seen much of here in the west from soviet 
political leaders in the past those moves took place behind the 
kremlins dark walls 
and shevardnadzes warning that if a dictatorship is created 
theres no guaranteeing who the next dictator will be must be 
considered 
but its clearly a warning more for gorbachev and the soviet 
people to consider than for us weve seen soviet dictators before 
our way is clear 
we must maintain a strong military force we have to keep the 
nato alliance viable arms reduction talks must continue but our 
negotiators should be as diligent as ever in assuring that any 
agreement reached is verifiable and enforceable 
and while we might prefer dealing with gorbachev and our 
interests may best be served if he remains the soviet leader we 
cant bank solely on him 
if shevardnadze was trying to tell us anything by his abrupt 
resignation that probably was it 
 
dec 23 
the providence ri journalbulletin on the soviet union 
for a year now everybody has been celebrating the end of the 
cold war recent events in the soviet union however might make us 
more comfortable with the word truce as disturbing as it is 
eduard shevardnadzes resignation as soviet foreign minister at 
least concentrates the attention of everyone east and west on the 
seriousness of the crisis in the soviet union 
does mikhail gorbachev really stand on the side of democracy and 
openness and how far is he willing to go to fight for these 
principles his enemies are at the gates perhaps within them and 
he cant dither too much longer before casting his lot 
the lesson for the west that we should not tie our plans too 
closely to individual leaders in a place as unpredictable as the 
soviet union and we should not necessarily expect the more benign 
regime of the recent past to continue 
it is worrying that powerful forces have expressed 
everincreasing resentment about the soviets declining world 
influence about the loss of control of eastern europe and so on 
the soviets will still be in a position to threaten the west if new 
leaders should decide to act on these resentments 
 
dec 24 
san francisco chronicle on the persian gulf 
generals have been known to fire from the verbal hip sometimes 
with a naive insouciance about just what it is they are saying 
and their words potential consequences 
in the case of lieutenant general calvin waller however this 
deputy commander of american forces in the gulf was simply being 
candid about what many have already intimated american troops are 
not yet at peak strength and efficiency for what may be an 
extremely difficult desert operation 
his words take some of the pressure off january 15 that looming 
date on which seemingly saddam would retreat or we would attack 
generals may be isolated but they sense the hazards of war more 
acutely than diplomats 
let the attack come if it must when we are ready 
 
dec 20 
beacon journal akron ohio on minority scholarships 
the bush administrations partial retreat from its assault 
against college scholarships for blacks and other minorities was 
wise but it did not go far enough 
in shifting gears rapidly and with clear nudges from an 
embarrassed white house michael l williams assistant secretary 
for civil rights in the us department of education left standing 
at least part of his original and unfortunate ban on scholarships 
designated for minorities 
in retreating however williams said colleges could award such 
scholarships without penalty as long as the money came from private 
donations or federal funds designed to aid minority students he 
then said colleges would not be allowed to use money from their 
general operating budgets for scholarships based on race 
how such a farreaching policy could have been set in motion 
without presidential knowledge defies understanding why it was not 
totally reversed is now even more of a mystery especially since 
bush made it clear ive long been committed to such 
scholarships 
 
</TEXT>
