<TEXT>
 
dec 20 
the repository canton ohio on the war on drugs 
lets not get too excited about those government figures that 
show a drop in the use of cocaine over the last five years lets 
just be cautiously optimistic 
health and human services secretary louis sullivan said the 
latest figures show some progress in the effort to change attitudes 
and drug habits and president bush said the statistics demonstrate 
that our hard work is paying off 
maybe so but were a long way from being out of the woods the 
statistics also reflect the fact that many adolescents are 
experimenting with drugs and the number of people who use cocaine 
daily has increased since 1988 
this means the nation has a long way to go before anyone can 
declare that the drug menace is under control we all must keep 
fighting 
 
dec 20 
the presscourier oxnard calif on commercial banks 
contrary to the chicken little scenarios gaining currency on 
capitol hill the banking industry is not about to go the way of 
the beleaguered savingsandloan system 
for starters banks have been more tightly regulated than the 
thrifts that stricter oversight is one reason banks made 26 
billion last year while the sampl industry lost 19 billion 
many thrifts disintegrated during a period when the government 
gave them a free hand to make risky investments under the cover of 
federally guaranteed deposit insurance banks always have been 
subject to much stricter government control 
in addition many failed sampls were undercapitalized and thus 
vulnerable to looting by larcenous managers as publicly held 
corporations major banks are required to open their books to 
public scrutiny so such abuses are much easier to detect promptly 
despite several weak years the banking industry is still 
capable of regaining its financial health with a timely assist from 
congress 
 
dec 24 
chicago tribune on the elections in haiti 
last weeks elections in haiti were praiseworthy for what didnt 
happen as well as for what did unlike in 1987 when 37 people died 
in election day violence at the hands of thugs believed backed by 
the army the military this time provided security at the polls 
rather than trying to subvert the democratic process 
voting was generally peaceful as 70 percent of registered 
haitians turned out to elect rev jeanbertrand aristide a priest 
who advocates liberation theology by a sizeable majority 
aristide appealed to the young and the poor by stressing 
selfreliance social justice economic reform and the elimination 
of corruption in a country where annual per capita income is under 
400 the poor are the constituency to champion from now on 
though it will be the powerholders the military business 
leaders landowners who can be expected to watch the 
priestpresidents every move looking for missteps to exploit for 
their selfish ends 
 
dec 19 
the commercial appeal memphis tenn on the messiness of 
democracy 
watching former dictatorships hold elections you realize what 
inexperience with freedom means what looks to a hardened westerner 
like the normal roughandtumble of a campaign may shock and 
mortify a pole 
in any event slander charges have been brought against 
stanislaw tyminski defeated in polands recent presidential race 
a curious upstart candidate who returned from 22 years in canada 
and peru to run from president tyminski got the worlds attention 
by outpolling the prime minister in the first round but then he 
lost by a big margin to lech walesa two weeks later after a bitter 
campaign 
tyminski enraged poles with his communist connections shady 
past and fierce attacks on the prime minister and walesa one 
local prosecutor overreacted however when the candidate falsely 
accused the government of selling off state property too cheaply 
if convicted of insulting the polish state tyminski could go to 
prison for six months to eight years 
one sympathizes with the wish that democratic politics could 
always be scrupulously fair campaigns always clean but veterans 
of democracy know better 
they know too that the way to counter a candidates lies is by 
exposing them publicly not by trotting out the very law the old 
communist government used to silence dissidents or anyone else it 
wanted to punish 
 
</TEXT>
