<DOCNO> AP901226-0047 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
 
dec 21 
the daily telegraph london on the soviet union 
the resignation of eduard shevardnadze provides dramatic 
confirmation of what the outside world has suspected fr months 
that the soviet union is teetering on the brink of dictatorship 
the enormous authority which parliament has handed to mr 
gorbachev his own prevarication over radical changes and his 
frequent references to the importance of law and order suggest that 
he is prepared to halt or even reverse internal reform for the 
sake of holding the country together 
 
dec 21 
the independent london on the soviet union 
the lights are going out in the soviet union the resignation of 
mr eduard shevardnadze is the despairing gesture of a sincere and 
exhausted man who does not want to be associated with the journey 
into darkness because he has supported reform so fully he takes 
with him a large portion of mr gorbachevs credibility he will 
also be a loss to his country in other ways for he played a 
central role in its opening to the world and its rapprochement with 
the west 
 
dec 23 
the sunday telegraph london on the soviet union 
much western piety surrounds western fears of soviet 
dictatorship doubtless it would be bad in comparison with 
western democracy and a free market but gorbachev seems incapable 
of creating that happy combination the democracy he has produced 
is it seems a drag on the free market 
instead of accepting the necessity for unemployment straight 
away as mrs thatcher did when she started reforming the british 
economy in the early eighties mr gorbachev encouraged people in 
the name of democracy to express dissent if they thought he was 
doing things wrongly those with vested interest in the existing 
order slowed him down the soviet union now has the blessings of 
political freedom but not the blessings of economic freedom 
a dictatorship might well be secure enough to withdraw 
guaranteed employment and thus force workers to emerge from their 
ageold sloth it could break up the collective farms and parcel 
them out among private owners just as those earlier dictators the 
first bolsheviks did the opposite farmers would then have the 
incentive to produce food for the city shops 
democracy and the free market are not dependent on each other 
that they exist together in the west is because of something akin 
to an evolutionary miracle asian countries with free markets have 
become rich without much democracy britain herself was the richest 
country in the world long before most of her people had the vote 
naturally we in the west fear a new soviet dictatorship because 
we fear it might revive the soviet military threat to us that is 
the only good reason for fearing it we should not continue 
sentimentally to suggest that mr gorbachevs freedoms and mr 
gorbachev himself are essential to the wellbeing of the soviet 
people 
 
dec 24 
the times london on the persian gulf crisis 
the gulf confrontation has revived the spirit in which the 
united nations was conceived a force for world order through which 
the civilized nations could join to counter aggression notably 
aggression against small states that many arab and third world 
nations have aligned themselves with this vision of a new world 
order is as significant as the unity between the superpowers 
what has emerged in the past six months is the possibility of a 
total realignment in the vast military might built up during the 
cold war a realignment in the cause not of regional selfdefense 
but of world order the world illserves itself by criticising the 
pain through which the united states is now passing as it debates 
its inevitably dominant role in this order 
american power for all its inadequacies its hesitations its 
ineptitudes remains unquestionably the best hope that civilized 
standards will triumph a high price may yet be extracted the gulf 
may erupt and swiftly give the lie to too much christmas optimism 
but war has never been a painless route to a greater peace the 
year fast closing has shown a glimpse of that peace and marked out 
the route there have been few more hopeful years than 1990 
 
dec 20 
straits times singapore on cambodia 
the irony might as yet turn against hanoi and its phnom penh 
satellite it is not they but the battle hardened and logistically 
strong khmer rouge that can gain most from a breakdown of the peace 
process 
without a return of more vietnamese troops to cambodia or the 
even more unlikely arrival of other sympathetic foreign forces 
the phnom penh regime is no position to deal with the khmer rouge 
militarily 
it would appear to be in the interests of all concerned 
therefore for vietnam and its lackeys to try and make a success of 
the talks on cambodia opening in paris this week 
using sovereignty as a wedge against peace is not only 
unsustainable but might prove to be counterproductive if there 
is no peace what cambodia will have is not sovereignty but war 
the khmer rouge has never been known to find that preference 
distasteful 
 
</TEXT>
