road as she drove home from her job at a carthage cheese plant jan 
11 1983 doctors said her brain was without oxygen for perhaps 20 
minutes 
she was given a feeding tube but was not put on a lifesupport 
system such as a ventilator 
ms cruzan lingered in a vegetative state her body rigid her 
feet and hands constricted and bent her fingernails sometimes 
digging into her wrists her eyes opened and moved erratically at 
times but doctors said she was as unconscious as someone in a coma 
and had no prospects for recovery 
an estimated 10000 americans are in such conditions 
she suffered from seizures vomiting bleeding gums and 
diarrhea her care at the staterun hospital cost missouri 
taxpayers 112000 a year 
ms cruzans case prompted state and federal righttodie 
legislation 
it also spurred interest in living wills which spell out a 
persons wish for treatment and in using power of attorney to 
authorize someone else to make medical decisions if the individual 
is unable to do so 
as of july at least 41 states and the district of columbia had 
living will laws which allow individuals to make their wishes 
about medical treatment known in advance of a crisis that may 
render them unable to speak 
in november president bush signed legislation creating a sort 
of medical miranda warning under the law effective in 
november 1991 patients in medicare or medicaidsupported 
hospitals or nursing homes must receive written information 
explaining their righttodie options under their state laws 
