<TEXT>
garry kasparov of the soviet union retained 
his title as world chess champion wednesday with a draw in the 22nd 
game defeating his longtime rival countryman anatoly karpov 
the pair ended the 22nd of the 24match chess championship 
series with a draw after 43 moves the halfpoint each player 
received put the 27yearold kasparov ahead 1210 allowing him to 
remain champion 
i was really nervous because i didnt know what to do whether 
to play for the win or draw kasparov said afterward then my 
life became much easier when i had the worse positions and i had 
to fight for the draw and i obliged 
though kasparov has clinched the title the two must play two 
more games to determine how the 3 million purse is split if there 
is a 1212 draw after 24 games the purse will be split evenly if 
kasparov gets another draw or win he gains 17 million 
kasparov won the title from karpov in 1985 at 22 he was the 
youngest champion in chess history he defended the crown by 
beating karpov in 1986 and 1987 
karpov had taken the championship in 1975 when american bobby 
fischer refused to defend the title he won in 1972 
kasparov playing white arrived promptly at the 5 pm 11 am 
edt wednesday the starting time at the palais des congres he 
fidgeted with his pieces awaiting the arrival of karpov then made 
his first move advancing his kings pawn before his rival 
entered 
the 39yearold challenger 10 minutes late made an identical 
first move 
they went into an opening known as the ruy lopez with the 
zaitsev variation seen before in the second fourth and 20th 
games kasparov won the second and the 20th using white 
but karpov playing aggressively pulled slightly ahead by the 
25th move and had two pawns well advanced before kasparov captured 
them 
by the 30th move kasparov had a pawn clear on the queens side 
of the board as well as three more pawns but black had a knight 
both players still had two bishops and their queens along with 
their kings 
the pair traded bishops and then on the 38th move karpov 
offered a queen exchange 
kasparov thought about it for 10 minutes and then moved his 
queen to put karpov in check 
karpov moved out of check but kasparov put karpov in check 
forcing a perpetual check situation 
karpov realizing the forced draw was the likely outcome looked 
at kasparov and shook hands implicitly offering the draw and 
giving kasparov the world title again 
kasparov showed little emotion talked over the game briefly 
with karpov and then smiled when being interviewed 
the two men who are known to dislike each other differ in 
temperment looks politics and playing style 
kasparov is talkative and flamboyant playing chess with 
creativity and decisiveness he is reformminded in his politics 
karpov is often protrayed as a colorless introvert who plays 
with surgical precision i have two loves karpov has said 
communism and chess 
normally chess is a battle between two individuals kasparov 
once said but in my case with karpov its a fight between two 
different mentalities in russia i identify him with the system 
ive been fighting 
the 22nd game had been delayed a week karpov had called a 
timeout saturday then the organizers called a technical timeout on 
christmas eve twice postponing the game 
kasparov rallied to beat karpov after committing what he called 
the worst blunder of my career during the first round of play 
in new york it occurred in the seventh game when kasparov 
misplayed a bishop and gave karpov an advantage that allowed the 
challenger to win and tie the series at 35 points each 
however kasparov won the previous three times he had white in 
the nine games in lyon karpov had only won twice in the 21 
previous games of the series 
the two soviet grandmasters had six draws in the french portion 
of the championship they drew 10 times in the 12 games played in 
new york between oct 8 and nov 7 
</TEXT>
