<TEXT>
the government wrongfully seized a rental 
building where tenants dealt drugs because the landlords were not 
allowed to defend themselves against the action an appeals court 
ruled wednesday 
the seizure was carried out under a federal civil forfeiture law 
that allows prosecutors to take property used for narcotics 
activity 
the 2nd us circuit court of appeals said a judge improperly 
approved the seizure based only on a finding that the owners 
harvey and helen lehrer were aware tenants dealt drugs in the 
brooklyn building 
the forfeiture law adopted by congress in 1988 includes a 
clause designed to protect landlords it states that the government 
cannot seize buildings if the owners can prove they had no 
knowledge of drug activity or that they made reasonable efforts 
to prevent illegal use of their property 
the court said the couple didnt get the chance to show they 
took steps to curtail drug activity 
the appeals court reversed an order approving the seizure and 
sent the case back to us district judge thomas platt to allow the 
lehrers to further defend themselves against the forfeiture 
in december 1988 drug enforcement administration agents raided 
the building and found heroin cocaine cash and drug 
paraphernalia after the raid the us attorneys office took 
steps to seize the building 
bernholtz said the building has been sealed and vacant since the 
raid 
