<TEXT>
the governments 1990 census figures awarded 
political clout to california and the south on wednesday and 
carried good news to republican presidential candidates for at 
least the rest of this century 
at the same time the numbers diminished the political strength 
of states in the northeast and midwest and set the stage for power 
struggles in every state except the six which now have only one 
congressional district each 
as a result of the census count congressional district lines 
will be redrawn in every state except those six and 19 
congressional seats will be shifted 
eight states will gain representation and power in congress 
thirteen will lose seats and clout 
california will be the chief gainer adding seven more 
congressional seats bringing its total to 52 florida will gain 
four going to 23 texas will gain three going to 30 and one 
additional seat in the house will go to five states arizona 
going to six georgia to 11 north carolina to 12 virginia to 
11 and washington to nine 
new york going down to 31 will lose three seats two seats 
will be lost by four states illinois going to 20 michigan to 
16 ohio to 19 and pennsylvania to 21 
eight states will lose one each iowa going to five kansas 
to four kentucky to six louisiana to seven massachusetts to 
10 montana to one new jersey to 13 and west virginia to 
three 
in presidential elections the figures make winning easier for 
republicans because states which the gop usually carries will gain 
votes in the electoral college while states which the democrats 
depend upon will have less importance 
a states number of votes in the electoral college equals the 
total of its congressmen and its two senators so in the 
presidential elections of 1992 and 1996 california which no 
democrat has carried in a presidential election since 1964 will 
have 54 of the 270 electoral votes a candidate needs to win the 
presidency or one out of five 
the other states with new electoral college importance are also 
in the west and sunbelt regions tending in recent years to go 
republican 
the political consequences advantage the republicans said 
stephen hess political analyst at the brookings institution a 
research organization the republican vote has tended to come 
more from the new west and the burgeoning sunbelt 
curtis gans director of the nonpartisan committee for the 
study of the american electorate disputed what he said was the 
widespread view of the census figures as a windfall for the 
republicans 
he said republicans will gain in congressional elections but 
only in the short run 
most states that gained seats did so because of growing hispanic 
populations gans said and hispanics of the class that is 
expanding the population in california florida new mexico and 
arizona tend to vote 21 democratic eventually thats going to 
tell probably within the next decade only in florida where 
cubanamericans favor conservative candidates can the republicans 
anticipate longterm gains he said 
redistricting battles will start soon in the 43 states which 
will have more than one representative in congress and they 
promise to be particularly painful in states which must eliminate 
seats held by incumbents 
in new york for example redistricting may mean that democratic 
reps charles schumer and stephen solarz both representing 
brooklyn will have to compete for a single seat in the game of 
musical chairs that a new census sets off every decade 
it is no coincidence hess said that both have built up 
campaign war chests in the milliondollar range anticipating a 
costly battle to stay in congress or perhaps a costly race for a 
post elsewhere perhaps the senate seat occupied by republican 
alfonse m damato 
the six states which have only one congressman and thus avoid 
redistricting are alaska delaware north dakota south dakota 
vermont and wyoming montana in losing a congressman in 1992 will 
join that list 
</TEXT>
