<TEXT>
iraqs invasion of kuwait and the heartstopping standoff that 
ensued in the persian gulf was by far the top news story of 1990 
according to a poll of associated press news editors and broadcast 
news directors 
the gulf crisis received 2506 points to finish well ahead of 
the news story that placed second the reunification of germany 
that story got 1460 points in voting by 327 editors and news 
directors 
the no 3 story also unfolded abroad the economic and 
political reforms that have racked the soviet union 
the first domestic story to make the list was the continuing 
savings and loan debacle which finished fourth 
finishing fifth was the warming of relations between the two 
superpowers followed by congress difficulties with the 1991 
budget americas economic downturn developments in eastern 
europe panama president manuel noriegas surrender and 
preparations to prosecute him and the end of the margaret thatcher 
era in britain 
the top 10 stories 
1 when saddam husseins iraqi troops overran the tiny emirate 
of kuwait in the predawn hours of aug 2 they set in motion a 
dizzying sequence of dangerous events a united nationsordered 
embargo against iraq a buildup of american and other forces in the 
region the taking of foreign hostages as human shields for iraqi 
military sites and their later release 
by septembers end the price of oil reached 40 a barrel 
nearly double what it had been before the invasion 
on nov 29 the un security council voted to give iraq until 
jan 15 to pull out of kuwait or face a possible military strike 
the world is waiting 
2 east and west germany became one nation again on oct 3 
ending a division that began at the end of world war ii 
reunification had been an impossible dream just a year before 
but that was before east german protests for democratic freedoms at 
the end of 1989 brought down berlin wall since 1961 the cold wars 
most palpable symbol 
free elections were held in east germany in the spring of 1990 
and the communists were sent packing the soviet union accepted 
nato membership for the united germany removing the last serious 
obstacle 
3 soviet president mikhail gorbachevs ambitious program of 
economic and political reforms foundered in 1990 although 
gorbachev won a new fiveyear term as president and tightened his 
control over the communist party his nation was torn apart by 
ethnic unrest rebellious republics disgruntled hardliners and 
shortages of bread sugar meat cigarettes and other goods 
4 the sampl mess got messier in 1990 and the tab to us 
taxpayers was revised upwards to 500 billion over 30 years the 2 
billion failure of charles keating jrs lincoln savings and loan 
the biggest bailout yet came to symbolize the troubles of hundreds 
of thrifts 
keating who faces federal fraud charges accusing him of 
misleading investors on the safety of junk bonds made 13 million 
in political contributions to five senators who intervened on his 
behalf with thrift regulators the senate ethics committee held 
hearings on the five donald w riegle jr dmich alan cranston 
dcalif john mccain rariz john glenn dohio and dennis 
deconcini dariz 
a federal judge found the presidents son neil guilty of 
conflict of interest for failing to disclose business ties with 
developers in his role as director of the failed silverado banking 
savings and loan association 
5 gorbachev may have faced mounting headaches at home but 
relations with the united states were never warmer bush and 
gorbachev who won the nobel peace prize for easing international 
tensions met three times during the year the first meeting was in 
washington to sign chemical weapons agreements the second was a 
oneday summit in helsinki finland to discuss the persian gulf 
crisis 
the third meeting was in paris in november for the 34nation 
conference on security and cooperation in europe its highlight was 
the signing of a farreaching conventional arms control agreement 
by leaders of north atlantic treaty organization countries and 
warsaw pact nations 
6 after five months of sometimes acrimonious negotiations 
congress and bush cobbled together a 1991 budget package in 
october in addition to spending cuts the 250 billion deficit 
reduction package provided for tax increases belying the 
presidents most popular pledge read my lips no new taxes 
republicans campaigning for reelection felt betrayed 
7 bush said the nations economy was in a serious slowdown 
federal reserve chairman alan greenspan used the phrase 
meaningful downturn but virtually everybody else was calling 
what was happening in the last half of 1990 a recession 
the statistics were mostly bad novembers unemployment rate 
jumped to a threeyear high of 59 percent singlefamily housing 
starts fell to levels unmatched since the 198182 recession the 
october trade deficit took an unexpected leap to 116 billion in 
october the worst monthly trade gap in 2 years the dow jones 
industrial average which had flirted with 3000 in july was some 
400 points lower in december 
in a bid to stimulate the economy the fed cut its discount rate 
the interest it charges on loans to member banks for the first 
time since 1986 
8 soviet troops began pulling out of poland czechoslovakia 
hungary and east germany after noncommunist governments came to 
power in those nations for the first time since world war ii but 
economic difficulties and ethnic tensions kept under wraps during 
communist rule flared under looser regimes and threatened the 
fledgling democracies 
in poland solidarity chairman lech walesa was elected president 
in a landslide victory in december 
romanians clashed with hungarians in disputed areas of romania 
and separatist demands threatened to dissolve yugoslavia in 
albania the last bastion of stalinist rule the government 
formally recognized the first opposition party in decades and 
scheduled elections for early 1991 the same week more than 150 
people were tried for antigovernment acts after protesters burned 
and ransacked buildings in four provinces 
9 on jan 3 panamanian president manuel noriega stepped out of 
the vatican mission where he had taken refuge and surrendered to 
us authorities he was brought to florida and charged with 
accepting 46 million in bribes to turn panama into a way station 
for colombian drug traffickers 
noriega had been scheduled to go to trial this january but his 
attorneys recently told a federal judge they will not be ready for 
trial until june 
10 margaret thatcher the iron lady who ruled britain longer 
than anyone else this century bowed out 
in 11 years as prime minister she dismantled britains version 
of socialism crushed obstructive labor unions and led a military 
victory against argentina in the falkland islands 
however her increasingly isolationist role in european 
community policies and her deeply unpopular poll tax cost her the 
support of her conservative party in november she was succeeded by 
her handpicked successor john major 
</TEXT>
