<TEXT>
some people who claim to know how free markets 
work are doing things that make you wonder such as raising their 
rates in an attempt to offset declines in business 
basic economics texts say that to do so is the road to ruin but 
dont try telling that to bankers and many other financial 
institutions executives who already have decided to put the theory 
through another test 
they wouldnt be the first to try for years automobile 
companies tried to cover higher costs by higher prices only to be 
forced by lagging sales into rebating some of the increases the 
steel industry tried it before them 
the wall street journal recently suggested that higher costs 
were behind its 50 percent price increase drawing from fortune 
magazine a commentary on the importance of reading the journals 
own freemarket editorials but the journal isnt the only 
publication by a long shot that is taking the higher price course 
its happening throughout the country 
with business falling you might think that financial 
institutions might consider lowering some fees for services but 
throughout the industry there are plans to raise them instead 
citibank raised several fees 25 percent or more 
savings institutions are working their way through an absolute 
financial debacle one that has swallowed up hundreds of outlets 
and scared away customers of many who survive but they too are 
doing it 
instituting or increasing fees for services can better define 
relationships with customers according to savings 
institutions published for members of the us league of savings 
institutions 
according to an article to boost fee income adds up in 
dollars and sense traditional fees involve services such as 
safedeposit boxes checks returned for insufficient funds 
stoppayment requests money transfers 
fees for many of these are sure to go up but it is likely that 
some notsocommon fees also will head in that direction in 
addition you may find that local branch managers will less apt to 
waive fees 
that latter practice says michael wilson a researcher for the 
league is often a key factor in the poor performance of some 
branches in the new thinking imposition of the fees may rid the 
branch of unprofitable customers 
the savings institutions article describes what it indicates 
is a highly profitable moneyraiser used by one bank it circulates 
a magazine to bigbalance customers and sells advertising in it 
thats not all 
more important it says is the real gravy which comes in 
the form of commissions paid by a travel agency on every cruise 
advertised in the magazine and booked by a bank customer 
will such practices work theoretically they arent likely to 
succeed over a long period of time if customers feel the services 
offered arent worth the price or are available at a better price 
from a competing institution 
however in a crisis and that is how many in the business view 
their condition they may help an institution to survive 
securities brokers did it you may recall and they survived for a 
while but with institutional business declining many are 
rethinking policies and seeking to attract individuals 
one of the key questions of course is whether the institutions 
will offer improved services or simply try to squeeze more money 
out of the existing level of service or perhaps even allow it to 
decline 
customers reaction will have something to say about it too will 
customers better appreciate the services offered when they have to 
pay for them or as could very well happen will they tend to feel 
exploited 
if you continue to believe that the laws of the market place of 
supply and demand havent been rescinded then you must still 
believe the practices may be a shortterm phenomenon and that 
price competition will return 
