<TEXT>
in his first opinion as a federal appeals 
judge a raymond randolph ruled against the administration that 
had just chosen him 
a conservative washington attorney nominated to the us circuit 
court of appeals by president bush earlier this year randolph 
rejected an administration argument that a board set up to regulate 
government nuclear weapons plants could meet secretly despite the 
freedom of information act 
his stinging opinion issued in october was joined by two 
conservative appointees of president reagan james l buckley and 
douglas h ginsburg 
between them bush and reagan have appointed more than 500 
federal judges over the past decade there are 34 vacancies now 
and bush recently signed a law creating 85 new judgeships around 
the country bringing the total number of federal trial and appeals 
judges to 828 
those appointments have established the dominance of 
conservatives on the federal bench but as the randolph ruling 
illustrates judges named for life are independent of the 
administrations that send them to the bench 
and legal scholars say the impact of ideology is overstated by 
lobbying groups involved in senate confirmation proceedings on 
federal district and circuit court judges 
the fact of the matter is there isnt much leeway on the part 
of courts below the supreme court said philip b kurland a 
constitutional law professor at the university of chicago the 
troops follow the direction of the commanding officers they go 
where they are told to and there are few mutineers in their 
ranks 
there has been a great deal of oversimplification and hype 
around this selection process and its impact said sheldon 
goldman a university of massachusetts political scientist who 
studies federal courts the impact is there but it is much more 
subtle than folks think or would like us to believe 
civil rights organizations and liberal advocacy groups have 
accused both reagan and bush of pursuing a longrange strategy to 
pack the federal courts with conservative ideologues 
during the reagan administration liberal opposition was a 
factor in the withdrawal of eight nominees to the federal bench and 
the rejection by the senate judiciary committee of three others 
the confirmation battles culminated in the democratcontrolled 
senates rejection 1987 of robert bork an outspoken conservative 
for a seat on the supreme court 
so far bushs judicial nominees have enjoyed smoother sailing 
in the senate 
the bush administration has tried to lower the thermostat in 
terms of the selection process goldman said 
reagan appointed a number of conservative theorists such as law 
professors richard posner frank easterbrook and stephen williams 
bush has generally appointed practicing lawyers with establishment 
republican credentials 
under bush there certainly isnt that effort to find 
professors whose judicial philosophies are carefully carved out 
there isnt that zealousness in trying to fit all their 
candidates through this very narrow prism said melanne verveer 
executive vice president of liberal group people for the american 
way 
bushs nominees bear an unmistakable conservative stamp but 
they are not necessarily of an ideological flavor said ae 
dick howard a university of virginia law professor they are 
people who are by and large of conservative temperament but whose 
background is not markedly political 
so far no bush nominee has been rejected by the judiciary 
committee but controversy looms next year 
the committee took no action for seven months on bushs 
nomination of kenneth ryskamp a miami federal judge accused of 
being hostile to civil rights to a seat on the 11th circuit court 
of appeals 
the nomination died when congress adjourned but ryskamp is 
expected to be renominated next year when lawmakers reconvene 
his membership in a private country club reputed to have once 
excluded blacks and jews and his pronouncements from the district 
bench could trigger the first senate confirmation fight over a 
bush judicial nominee 
people for the american way has noted in mailings to its members 
that ryskamp ruled against the plaintiffs in all but four of 41 
cases involving civil and constitutional rights that came before 
him nine of ryskamps civil rights rulings were reversed by the 
appellate court to which he was nominated 
critics also point to a case in which the judge told some black 
teenagers who had been attacked by police dgs that it might not 
be inappropriate to carry around a few scars to remind you or your 
wrongdoing in the past 
a renewed ryskamp nomination could end two years of relative 
peace between the democratic senate and the republican white house 
on judicial nominees 
end adv ams fri dec 28 
