<TEXT>
a presidential panel on rural development says 
in its final report that future planners should keep in mind that 
there are many perceptions of rural america and its people 
including some that are not very accurate 
the 15member national commission on agriculture and rural 
development policy said that definitions of rural america 
abound and that what appears to be rural in one part of the 
nation may seem pretty citified in another 
but the commission which was authorized in the expiring 1985 
farm law shied away from offering a single definition of rural 
the chairman of the commission is charles pete knigge a 
dairy and grain farmer from omro wis 
other members representing diverse interests and regions 
include other farmers and officials of agricultural organizations 
representatives of agricultural industries and financial 
institutions public office holders and educators 
the massive 1990 farm law includes a rural development package 
along with a provision that creates a new rural development 
administration within the agriculture department 
many of the existing development programs in the farmers home 
administration for example would be transferred to the new 
agency 
the commissions report which was sent to president bush 
earlier this month put the formation of a national rural 
development policy at the top of the agenda 
no giant federal spending programs were recommended federal 
advice expertise and other such help should be available but 
rural people will have to settle their own problems 
the term rural america has come to include farms and forested 
areas mining and manufacturing areas isolated small towns and 
places under the growing influence of nearby urban centers the 
report said 
however it added if policy is to effectively address rural 
needs there must be a clear understanding of the character of 
rural america 
popular beliefs about rural america are based on many 
perceptions the report said some if once true no longer 
are these misperceptions mayobscure true conditions in rural 
areas and divert policies in directions that are inappropriate to 
modern rural needs 
the commission listed five major points to help confront and 
refute misperceptions relating to rural development policy the 
facts based on the report include 
most rural americans no longer depend mainly on farming for 
their jobs and income 
agriculture is one of the nations biggest industries and is the 
source of food and fiber for domestic and export consumption in 
many states and rural areas agriculture is the leading source of 
basic income in the economy 
but less than 10 percent of the rural work force is directly 
employed in farming in most rural areas other industries 
especially manufacturing and services have eclipsed farming as a 
primary source of livelihood 
rural america is more than smalltown farmcentered midwestern 
communities 
the national perception of rural is heavily influenced by 
images of smalltown america popularized in films and television 
where the simple life persists 
the largest numbers of rural americans live in the south where 
they are more likely to work at manufacturing jobs than in farming 
and in the midwest where much of the nations food production 
occurs 
still others call western and new england communities home far 
from being monopolized by farm trade centers rural america is made 
up of a diverse array of fishing villages in coastal areas mining 
towns in appalachia and the west mill towns in the southeast and 
tourist centers near national parks and natural attractions 
each of these communities faces different challenges 
not all of rural america is losing population 
during the mid1980s more rural counties lost population than 
grew over the entire decade more people moved out of rural 
america than moved into it 
but these totals obscure the rapid growth that sometimes occurs 
in many parts of rural america 
in areas that have highquality natural amenities such as 
coastline mountains or a warm climate large numbers of retirees 
and vacationers have made them among the fastest growing areas in 
the nation 
both growing and declining rural areas face difficult problems 
population losses cause strains for communities trying to 
provide basic services sometimes this threatens their survival as 
social and economic units 
growing communities whose expanding populations bring new tax 
dollars and vitality do not suffer from declining services and 
property values but growth especially if its rapid creates 
other problems including new residents with values and 
expectations that differ from those of existing residents 
rapid growth can also put pressure on community services and 
institutions to keep pace with rising demands rising property 
assessments that challenge lowincome residents to meet growing tax 
obligations and the prospect that new job opportunities may go to 
new residents leaving few benefits for longtime citizens 
many rural residents live in poverty 
one in seven rural americans mostly in the south have incomes 
below the official government poverty level of 12675 a year for a 
family of four the rural poor are likely to be working poor 
people with jobs many families have two or more fulltime workers 
whose wages are too low even to yield a povertylevel income 
the report added concentrated in minority groups the poor 
live in areas that have been bypassed by economic growth leaving 
them few alternatives to the meager jobs they hold 
their inability to afford proper health care results in 
disabilities that limit their ability to perform the manual labor 
jobs on which they often depend their poor schools provide them 
with educations inadequate to qualify them for better paying 
jobs 
</TEXT>
