merger talks between pan am corp and trans 
world airlines inc were on hold today after twa chairman carl 
icahn accused pan am of showing a lack of good faith 
pan am and twa negotiated through the weekend and into monday 
over whether twa would lend pan am enough money to keep it 
operating until the struggling carriers can merge 
twa spokesman don morrison said pan ams representatives 
canceled a monday meeting to discuss the offer and no talks were 
held tuesday 
pan am spokesman jeff kreindler denied tuesday that talks had 
broken off he said the next step is for mr icahn to submit a 
definitive offer to the company 
we also indicated there would have to be bridge financing 
until the deal could close he said 
pan am on friday accepted icahns buyout offer of 150 in cash 
and about 1 in preferred stock or notes for each of pan ams 150 
million outstanding shares as long as twa made the loan the deal 
would value the airline at about 375 million 
icahn launched his offer for pan am as he announced plans to 
sell all of twas london routes and some other assets to a 
healthier rival american airlines in a package worth 625 
million 
icahn has sought assurances that pan am could repay the loan 
estimated at as much as 100 million icahn has proposed forwarding 
pan am debtorinpossession financing that would put twa first 
in line for repaymen t during a pan am bankruptcy reorganization 
in a monday letter to pan am corp chairman thomas plaskett 
