<DOCNO> AP901226-0171 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
standard amp poors corp and the chicago board 
options exchange said wednesday they had settled a lawsuit in which 
sampp charged the exchange with violating a 1983 licensing agreement 
the two sides said they had signed anagreement extending the 
cboes exclusive license to trade options on the sampp 500 index and 
the sampp 100 index two important measures of stock market activity 
sampp a subsidiary of mcgrawhill inc in early november charged 
the chicago exchange with wrongly asserting an exclusive right to 
use the indexes on financial products other than options contracts 
traded on the exchange the cboe denied any breach 
a person familiar with the outofcourt settlement said it 
reaffirms sampps ability to license debt instruments and other 
products using the sampp 100 and 500 indexes other than options 
contracts 
there was no monetary settlement said the official who asked 
not to be identified by name the lawsuit had been filed in 
manhattan federal court 
the new agreement also extends until 1998 the cboes exclusive 
right to trade options contracts based on the two indexes 
a cboe spokesman said the exchange would not comment on the 
terms or conditions of the agreement mcgrawhill spokeswoman 
elizabeth russo said the agreement was mutually satisfactory 
the sampp 100 index and sampp 500 index measure stock performance 
and are traded in units on the nations major options exchanges 
options give an investor the right to buy or sell a security at a 
specified time for a specific price 
sampp had said its license limits the cboe to options contracts on 
the two indexes that are traded on a securities exchange and 
settled through an established clearing house by payment of cash or 
the underlying security 
sampp said the cboes rights do not apply to other financial 
instruments that offer a return based in whole or part on the two 
indexes those include notes certificates of deposit and other 
debt instruments products that trade over the counter and 
financial instruments issued by institutions other than an 
exchange 
the dispute began when sampp withdrew a note offering for denmark 
earlier this year that paid interest based on the sampp 500 
underwriters for the issue were said to have withdrawn from the 
deal because of challenges by cboe officials to use of the index 
sampp a financial information and credit rating agency for 
several years has licensed the rights to use its indexes in 
connection with financial products sold off of exchanges 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

